Not really a serious problem. Someone diagnosed that late in life is called "high functioning" on the scale. Yes, there are some personality quirks, but nothing worse than what we run into any other person who's a touch odd. The fact that she's diagnosed is a bonus since she will get help, meds, and people actually know what's wrong with her. As she does. There are quite a number of therapies, activities. and self-training exercises she and teh people around her can engage in. She will not only get better (rather than worse) over time, but people with a 'light touch' of Asperger's are generally very bright. She will be delightfully intelligent, engaging, and creative. Big win in Life's Lottery.

Another aspect that's positive is that Asperger's people are some of the least psychotic, psychopathic, sociopathic people in society. They tend to be very open, honest, and loving. Part of their difficulty in adjusting to society is the assholes and sociopaths they have to deal with that the rest of us consider to be "normal," even "successful businessmen." Asperger folks have a nearly impossible time understanding that sort of mental illness because it's so dishonest, manipulative, and twisted.

> t. I've spent a few years around, teaching, and working with higher-functioning Asperger's people.
